You mean four. Note this is four decisions that were incorrect, rather than 'dubious'. As in confirmed to be mistakes and PGMOL apologised for.

>>129092539
Arguably one of the best stats out there for footy, but midwits kneejerk react to it without knowing how it works.

Basically a database of 100s of thousands of games has been made recording every goalscoring chance in those games, keeping track of where the shot was taken from, how many defenders were between player and goal, whether player was under pressure form a defender, etc. etc. etc. and then record how often from such a position and defensive situation a goal was scored, (e.g. a big chance might be xG 0.33, i.e. a 1/3 chance of scoring). They all get added up and explain to you after which team actually created more high value chances and actually is the closest thing to a non-headcannon, objective look at what happened in a game.
Doesn't mean the team with a higher xG deserves to win, etc. etc. etc. But it does show if your team is consistently scoring more goals than their xG that they are basically on a lucky run and fluking it or have some genuine goal scoring talent, while scoring significantly less than the xG shows that they are doing better than the results give credit and maybe also that the finishing is shit and a new striker is needed.

A bit hard to get the data for free, but comparing top strikers' goals scored with xG, for example, is actually a pretty strong argument for whether a striker is truly world class or actually overhyped.

tl;dr All statistics are shit, this is one of the better ones, up there with assists and goals scored.

Part of the reason why ties are accepted in soccer is that it's a low scoring game.
I think it's something like a third of games that a draws.
It's already common for teams to sort of play for a draw. Or be happy at times with a draw.
Keep in mind in soccer the defense and offense is playing at the same time. So part of the tactics is to balance the two.
If you gave a win after a draw.
Let's say you had a penalty shoot out after a draw. Then a lot of teams would be even more defensive and just hope to win the penalties.
So you don't want it in soccer except for knockout tournaments were you have to.
Keep in mind that you get 3 points for a win and 1 for a draw.
If two teams split wins they get 3 points each
If they they draw they get 2 each.
It's to encourage playing for the win and punish draws because a draw usually means a low scoring game.
So a penalty shootout in the end of the game would be a benefit to shitty boring teams. It would reward defensive play.

extra innings happen around 10% of games
Plus in baseball the offense and defense split to a certain extent.
They overlap in fielding and batting.
But the whole concept of playing defensively and trying to get a draw isn't a concept anyway.
Teams are not trying to get draws and i don't know that there is a correlation between getting to extra innings and playing badly.
(I could be wrong about that though)

Kneeling in America was a protest to be done during the playing of the national anthem. It makes sense because they play the anthem before every pro sports match. And kneeling during the anthem, rather than standing, is supposed to be an act of rebellion, and an expression of discontent with the state of the nation. I don't agree with what Kaepernick was trying to say with his protest, but I acknowledge that it made sense and was effective.

Kneeling as it is done in football, on the other hand, is utterly retarded because nobody does it during the anthems. They do it randomly, in complete silence, for a few seconds before the match kicks off. This version of kneeling never caught on in America because they probably recognise it makes no sense, but in the UK it has somehow become some kind of religious ceremony that footballers, pundits and managers all believe must be performed as often as possible.

>>129193254
The Premier League is the strongest league overall thanks to a massive money influx. It is extremely international and the most commercialized. The play is very demanding, traditionally known for physicality (which isn't that true anymore imho), but by now, there is technique as well of course. Most teams play rather offensively, there is a lot of space for attacks. It simply has the best players overall because the clubs are the richest. It's also the only league with more than two teams who could be called "(potentially) dominant" in the last years.
La Liga is regarded as the second-best league, but they are in a small downwards spiral now that Messi and Ronaldo are gone. Play is known for very high level of technique. It's not as balanced as the Premier League, the gap between top teams and bottom feeders is larger.
Bundesliga is the third-best league in the UEFA rankings. It has the highest attendance numbers of all leagues and probably the best atmosphere. Play is very offensive, but like a mix of the stereotypical attributes of the aforementioned two leagues. Bayern is by far the most dominant club, especially in recent years. The rest of the league is very balanced.
Serie A is the fourth in UEFA rankings. Traditionally, the play is said to be very defensive and tactics-focused. It's not quite as simple, of course. Lots of big names, but they tend to lack success in Europe in the last years.
Ligue 1 is number five and known for producing talents, the league produces ngubus en masse and play is quick. PSG is very dominant, but not as ruthless and constant as Bayern.
Eredivisie is also known for producing talents. It is number six right now. Three important teams.
Primeira Liga also has three notable teams and has produced quite many talents, here as well, the play is said to be about technique first and foremost.

"Good" and "bad" is hard to say. I gave you the current order of the UEFA rankings. But it's not only that of course

You fags might laugh at me but I had sciatica quite badly for a long while (was in the Marine corps, but had it even before then). The biggest thing that helped me get rid of it was ditching traditional “””running shoes””” in favor of either minimalist or five finger shoes.
Seemed to put my stride or on my mid foot, allowing my calves to act as shock absorbers, whereas when I had other types of shoes I was running with my heel striking the ground first, sending a shock up my leg.

Just my two cents. Also yoga.

To stretch your lower back out:

1. Lay down flat on your stomach. Feet shoulder width apart.
2. Do a pushup where you are using only your arms/shoulders to lift your upper torso.
3. Do this 10 times. 2 or 3 times per day.

To me the debate with Rodgers just revolves around his talent. He didn't consistently dominate anything outside the Bears and he's mediocre in the post season lacking any accomplishments set him apart. He throws some of the prettiest passes in history so the media is extra willing to bend over backwards to create excuses and narratives for him and that's only recently stopped. The Packers organization is one of the best in the league, especially from a team-building standpoint but it's often portrayed like they're mediocre or among the worst. They've built great defenses but Rodgers can't elevate the offense and they've build great offenses but Rodgers can't overcome the defense. They're rarely bad at any part of the team. That's sort of why I tank him in these debates since he's literally just a great talent and nothing more. Marino has a better arm and elevated bad/mediocre Dolphins teams to consistently be really good but not great. Young has better legs and consistently made good Niners teams look great.

When it comes to Favre, Bradshaw, and Staubach the difference in physical talent is made up for mental toughness, leadership and just a great philosophy in their playstyles. They consistently elevated their teams and never shut down in big games to protect their stats so they won't be blamed for a loss. Rodgers always provided a consistent floor for his teams but their ceilings were always capped because Rodgers cannot elevate. It disqualifies him from any top 10 debate in my opinion. You say Drew Brees is never considered the best during his time yet him and Rodgers effectively had the same amount of impact on their teams.
